By 1979, 13 companies had decided to become members of IFPRI (Table 1
                     ). Howard Turner had retired from DuPont to become the first IFPRI President and Reg Davies from DuPont was elected by the members as the first TC Chair. The first IFPRI Annual General Meeting (AGM) was held in Philadelphia in June of 1979 where 3 research papers and one review were presented (Table 2
                     ). A substantial portion of the meeting was also devoted to the discussion of new projects to be funded, assessment of the current research, and discussion of the general state of funding and education in the area of particle science and technology. All of these would become a regular part of future IFPRI meetings. Over the next 4Â years under Howard Turner's leadership, membership in IFPRI grew to 22 members (Fig. 1
                     ) and the research program grew to include 12 research presentations and 3 reviews (Fig. 2
                     ). It was during this initial start-up of the IFPRI organization that many of the organizational details were determined including:

                           1)

defining 5 areas of industrial important research (Fig. 3
                              ): Characterization, Size Reduction, Formation, Dry Systems or Powder Flow, and Wet Systems (filtration and rheology),


                           2)

holding the AGM in June or July, alternating each year between the US and Europe and in Japan every 5Â years,


                           3)

holding a second meeting in January for the EC to assess the current state of the organization, develop business strategies, and consider the financial state of IFPRI,


                           4)

having a third meeting in March for the TC (industrial members only) to consider the current research program and plan on new programs for the coming year, and


                           5)

developing some of the collegial networking such as annual banquets, happy hours, sporting events, and other interpersonal activities that provide the human glue that binds any organization.
